    <item>
      <title>Phase 1 — Requirement Clarification</title>
      <link>http://localhost:1313/learning/advanced-skills/system-design-practice/intermediate-systems/3_api-rate-limiter/1_phase1/1_1_requirement_clarification/</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>http://localhost:1313/learning/advanced-skills/system-design-practice/intermediate-systems/3_api-rate-limiter/1_phase1/1_1_requirement_clarification/</guid>
      <description>&lt;h2 id=&#34;1-why-clarification-matters&#34;&gt;1. Why Clarification Matters&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;hr&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Before choosing an algorithm, we must clarify what kind of rate limiter we are building.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;A rate limiter can behave very differently depending on:&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;ul&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;who is being limited&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;what limit is applied&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;how the time window is calculated&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;what happens when the limit is exceeded&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;/ul&gt;&#xA;&lt;blockquote&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;📝 &lt;strong&gt;Key Point:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br&gt;&#xA;Rate limiting is not just about counting requests — it is about enforcing a clear traffic policy.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&#xA;&lt;hr&gt;&#xA;&lt;h2 id=&#34;2-clarification-questions-interview-conversation&#34;&gt;2. Clarification Questions (Interview Conversation)&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;hr&gt;&#xA;&lt;h3 id=&#34;q1--who-are-we-limiting&#34;&gt;Q1 — Who are we limiting?&lt;/h3&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;You:&lt;/strong&gt; Are we limiting requests by user, IP address, API key, tenant, or endpoint?&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Phase 1 — Naive Approach</title>
      <link>http://localhost:1313/learning/advanced-skills/system-design-practice/intermediate-systems/3_api-rate-limiter/1_phase1/1_2_naive-approach/</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>http://localhost:1313/learning/advanced-skills/system-design-practice/intermediate-systems/3_api-rate-limiter/1_phase1/1_2_naive-approach/</guid>
      <description>&lt;h2 id=&#34;1-why-start-with-a-naive-approach&#34;&gt;1. Why Start with a Naive Approach?&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;hr&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Before jumping into advanced algorithms like sliding window or token bucket, we should first build a simple working solution.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;The goal is to understand the core idea:&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;div class=&#34;highlight&#34;&gt;&lt;pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34; style=&#34;color:#f8f8f2;background-color:#272822;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4;-webkit-text-size-adjust:none;&#34;&gt;&lt;code class=&#34;language-text&#34; data-lang=&#34;text&#34;&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;&gt;&lt;span&gt;For each client, count how many requests they have made in the current time window.&#xA;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;blockquote&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;📝 &lt;strong&gt;Key Point:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br&gt;&#xA;A naive solution is useful because it gives us a correct baseline before we improve the design.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Phase 1 — Fixed Window Counter</title>
      <link>http://localhost:1313/learning/advanced-skills/system-design-practice/intermediate-systems/3_api-rate-limiter/1_phase1/1_3_fixed-window-counter/</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>http://localhost:1313/learning/advanced-skills/system-design-practice/intermediate-systems/3_api-rate-limiter/1_phase1/1_3_fixed-window-counter/</guid>
      <description>&lt;h2 id=&#34;1-what-is-fixed-window-counter&#34;&gt;1. What is Fixed Window Counter?&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;hr&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Fixed Window Counter is one of the simplest rate limiting algorithms.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;It works by dividing time into &lt;strong&gt;fixed intervals (windows)&lt;/strong&gt; and counting the number of requests in each window.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;div class=&#34;highlight&#34;&gt;&lt;pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34; style=&#34;color:#f8f8f2;background-color:#272822;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4;-webkit-text-size-adjust:none;&#34;&gt;&lt;code class=&#34;language-text&#34; data-lang=&#34;text&#34;&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;&gt;&lt;span&gt;For each client:&#xA;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;&gt;&lt;span&gt;Count requests in a fixed time window&#xA;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;&gt;&lt;span&gt;Reset the counter when the window changes&#xA;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;hr&gt;&#xA;&lt;h2 id=&#34;2-how-it-works&#34;&gt;2. How It Works&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;hr&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Assume:&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;div class=&#34;highlight&#34;&gt;&lt;pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34; style=&#34;color:#f8f8f2;background-color:#272822;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4;-webkit-text-size-adjust:none;&#34;&gt;&lt;code class=&#34;language-text&#34; data-lang=&#34;text&#34;&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;&gt;&lt;span&gt;Limit = 100 requests per minute&#xA;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;p&gt;Time is divided into windows like:&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Phase 1 — Sliding Window Algorithm</title>
      <link>http://localhost:1313/learning/advanced-skills/system-design-practice/intermediate-systems/3_api-rate-limiter/1_phase1/1_4_sliding-window-algorithm/</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>http://localhost:1313/learning/advanced-skills/system-design-practice/intermediate-systems/3_api-rate-limiter/1_phase1/1_4_sliding-window-algorithm/</guid>
      <description>&lt;h2 id=&#34;1-why-do-we-need-sliding-window&#34;&gt;1. Why Do We Need Sliding Window?&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;hr&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;In the previous approach (Fixed Window Counter), we saw a major issue:&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;div class=&#34;highlight&#34;&gt;&lt;pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34; style=&#34;color:#f8f8f2;background-color:#272822;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4;-webkit-text-size-adjust:none;&#34;&gt;&lt;code class=&#34;language-text&#34; data-lang=&#34;text&#34;&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;&gt;&lt;span&gt;Boundary Burst Problem&#xA;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;p&gt;Example:&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;div class=&#34;highlight&#34;&gt;&lt;pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34; style=&#34;color:#f8f8f2;background-color:#272822;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4;-webkit-text-size-adjust:none;&#34;&gt;&lt;code class=&#34;language-text&#34; data-lang=&#34;text&#34;&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;&gt;&lt;span&gt;12:00:59 → 100 requests&#xA;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;&gt;&lt;span&gt;12:01:00 → 100 requests&#xA;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;p&gt;Result:&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;div class=&#34;highlight&#34;&gt;&lt;pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34; style=&#34;color:#f8f8f2;background-color:#272822;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4;-webkit-text-size-adjust:none;&#34;&gt;&lt;code class=&#34;language-text&#34; data-lang=&#34;text&#34;&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;&gt;&lt;span&gt;200 requests in ~1 second ❌&#xA;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;p&gt;This happens because each window is treated independently.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;hr&gt;&#xA;&lt;blockquote&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;📝 &lt;strong&gt;Goal:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br&gt;&#xA;Smooth out request distribution across time instead of resetting abruptly.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&#xA;&lt;hr&gt;&#xA;&lt;h2 id=&#34;2-what-is-sliding-window&#34;&gt;2. What is Sliding Window?&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;hr&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Sliding Window removes the concept of rigid boundaries.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Phase 1 — Token Bucket &amp; Leaky Bucket</title>
      <link>http://localhost:1313/learning/advanced-skills/system-design-practice/intermediate-systems/3_api-rate-limiter/1_phase1/1_5_token-bucket/</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>http://localhost:1313/learning/advanced-skills/system-design-practice/intermediate-systems/3_api-rate-limiter/1_phase1/1_5_token-bucket/</guid>
      <description>&lt;h2 id=&#34;1-why-do-we-need-another-algorithm&#34;&gt;1. Why Do We Need Another Algorithm?&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;hr&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;So far we have seen:&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;div class=&#34;highlight&#34;&gt;&lt;pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34; style=&#34;color:#f8f8f2;background-color:#272822;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4;-webkit-text-size-adjust:none;&#34;&gt;&lt;code class=&#34;language-text&#34; data-lang=&#34;text&#34;&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;&gt;&lt;span&gt;Fixed Window → simple but bursty&#xA;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;&gt;&lt;span&gt;Sliding Window → accurate but memory heavy&#xA;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;p&gt;We now want a solution that:&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;div class=&#34;highlight&#34;&gt;&lt;pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34; style=&#34;color:#f8f8f2;background-color:#272822;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4;-webkit-text-size-adjust:none;&#34;&gt;&lt;code class=&#34;language-text&#34; data-lang=&#34;text&#34;&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;&gt;&lt;span&gt;- allows small bursts&#xA;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;&gt;&lt;span&gt;- enforces a steady rate&#xA;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;&gt;&lt;span&gt;- uses minimal memory&#xA;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;hr&gt;&#xA;&lt;blockquote&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;📝 &lt;strong&gt;Goal:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br&gt;&#xA;Balance flexibility (bursts) with control (rate limiting).&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&#xA;&lt;hr&gt;&#xA;&lt;h2 id=&#34;2-what-is-token-bucket&#34;&gt;2. What is Token Bucket?&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;hr&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Token Bucket is one of the most widely used rate limiting algorithms in production systems.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
